<dl id="n25186k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25186k">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25186k"> 186(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> papa / pontiff</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Tertullian called the Holy Spirit the &ldquo;vicar of Christ&rdquo;; he says sarcastically, &ldquo;No doubt he is a Pontifex Maximus who calls himself a bishop of bishops.&rdquo; He knew not that medi&aelig;val Popes would usurp such titles, and that the priest-king, as successor of the divine Augusti, would assume the office of the old Roman <mark>pontiff</mark> who &ldquo;made the bridge&rdquo; leading to heaven. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 321-2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14126m" href="c14all.htm#c14126m">VI.C.14:126(m)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
